step.reason:
%text
The line joining any two points has a slope.
When a third point is said to be on this same
line, then the slope formed by any pair of
two points is equal. Therefore,
%
\qquad\underbrace{\dfrac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}}_{\text{slope}_{12}}
  =\underbrace{\dfrac{y_3-y_2}{x_3-x_2}}_{\text{slope}_{23}}
  =\underbrace{\dfrac{y_3-y_1}{x_3-x_1}}_{\text{slope}_{31}}

%text
$A=(k, 3),\, B=(6, -2)$ and $C=(-3, 4)$
%

\begin{align}
  \text{slope}_{AB} &= \dfrac{-2-3}{6-k} \\
  \text{slope}_{BC} &= \dfrac{4-(-2)}{-3-6}
\end{align} \\
%text
The two slopes are equal therefore,
%
\begin{align}
  &\dfrac{-2-3}{6-k}=\dfrac{4-(-2)}{-3-6} \\
  \implies &\dfrac{-5}{6-k}=\dfrac{6}{-9} \\
  \implies &\dfrac{-5}{6-k}=\dfrac{2}{-3} \\
  \implies & 15=12-2k \implies k=-\dfrac{3}{2}
\end{align}
